This lab is the corequisite for the CHEM101 lecture. It aims to cover chemistry lab technique, especially concerning the determination of chemical and physical properties and the process of chemical synthesis. The class has an additional lab fee of $150. The course fulfills the Quantitative Data Analysis requirement for the College of Arts and Sciences.

Students widely referred to this course as “mainly a reinforcement” of high-school chemistry, although some students claimed they gained valuable new knowledge about lab technique. Readings and labs were considered much more insightful than lectures. Overall, students tended to rate the course as “well organized and interesting.”&#8232;

Students gave glowing reviews of Professor Phillips in all respects, calling her personable, “very funny,” and clear in her PowerPoints. Students especially noted Professor Phillips' accessibility; she was “eager and willing to help” and “responded to every email promptly.” &#8232;

Most students were freshmen taking the lab as a major or distributional requirement. They unanimously rated the course as easy and having a low workload: there were “only 5 labs,” and “exams were incredibly easy.” Some students complained that there was “too much hand-holding,” although this was appreciated as a break from the difficulty of the accompanying lecture.

